@Generated(value="com.guidewire.pl.metadata.codegen.Codegen", comments="CheckRecurrence.eti;CheckRecurrence.eix;CheckRecurrence.etx") public abstract class CheckRecurrence extends com.guidewire.pl.persistence.code.BeanBase implements Extractable, Retireable
CheckRecurrence Describes the frequency that Checks in a RecurringCheck are issued. Abstract supertype of MonthlyCheckRecurrence and WeeklyCheckRecurrence.

    • cloneRecurrence

      public CheckRecurrence cloneRecurrence(CheckSet newCheckSet)
      Creates a clone of this CheckRecurrence, either weekly or monthly as appropriate. In either case copies in critical base values, and also sets firstDueDate to next date in recurrence (After last occurrence date of recurrence being copied). If cloned check/checkgroup has exposure with service period, this method also generates the proper service period for the new check(s).

    • getPublicID

      public String getPublicID()
      The external ID for this entity.

      PublicID values are automatically created during the commit, if not previously set. The format is random, meeting security requirements based on current industry standards. For example:

      • pc:SYinDB2XTOgNZFs1NpxU8
      • pc:Sf8QS4N5RBS-h8_pj-Oy_
      • pc:SBwBzylneecSNr6_Ub4IO
      Your configuration code must not assume any particular format for PublicID values, in either the prefix or body portion of the string, or even assume the existence of a prefix. Do not make any assumptions at all about the content of a PublicID value, including expectations that values are sequential, numeric, or prefixed.

      You can subclass and override AbstractBundleTransactionCallback.afterSetIds(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle) if you need to see the value in the same commit. 

      
  var note = new Note(bundle)
  bundle.addBundleTransactionCallback(new AbstractBundleTransactionCallback() {
     override function afterSetIds(b : Bundle) {
       log.info("Created Note " + note.PublicID)
     }
  })
      Specified by:

    • hasEditableChecks

      public boolean hasEditableChecks()
      Tests whether this recurrence contains any checks that are still editable.

      Note: For efficiency when dealing with large recurrences, if this bean is not new, this method performs a query against the database. If you aren't worried about loading large recurrences into the bundle, you can determine whether there are editable checks on a recurrence against the bundle by evaluating EditableChecks and testing the length of the result.

      Returns:
      true if the recurrence contains at least one editable check, else false
